<barrons:explanation>
<![CDATA[<TextFlow xmlns="http://ns.adobe.com/textLayout/2008">
<p><span fontWeight="bold">3 + π</span></p>
<p lineHeight="32">Since each radius is 3, <span fontStyle="italic">OA</span> = <span fontStyle="italic">OB</span>, and so m<img dominantBaseline="ideographicCenter" source="assets/images/tst2_eqn_069.swf"/></p>
<p lineHeight="120%"><img source="assets/images/tst2_s3_019b.swf"/></p>
<p lineHeight="32">Then, <img dominantBaseline="ideographicCenter" source="assets/images/tst2_eqn_070.swf"/> Therefore, Δ<span fontStyle="italic">AOB</span> is equilateral, and <span fontStyle="italic">AB</span> = 3. The length of arc <span fontStyle="italic">AB</span> is <img dominantBaseline="ideographicCenter" source="assets/images/tst2_eqn_071.swf"/> of the circumference. <img dominantBaseline="ideographicCenter" source="assets/images/tst2_eqn_072.swf"/>, so the length of arc <span fontStyle="italic">AB = </span>π. The perimeter of the region, then, is 3 + π.</p>
<p></p>
<p><span fontWeight="bold">Alternative Solution:</span></p>
<p lineHeight="32">Trust the diagram. <span fontStyle="italic">AB</span> looks about the same as <span fontStyle="italic">OB</span>, so assume it is 3, and arc <span fontStyle="italic">AB</span> is clearly slightly bigger. Hence, the perimeter is a little more than 6. <img dominantBaseline="ideographicCenter" source="assets/images/tst2_eqn_073.swf"/> and <img source="assets/images/tst2_eqn_074.swf"/> + π are both less than 5, which is definitely too small. Guess between 3 + π and <img source="assets/images/tst2_eqn_075.swf"/> + π. 3 + π is the better guess, because <span fontStyle="italic">AB might be</span> exactly 3.</p>
<p></p>
